Ok, there are several issues here.

1.  Which has a faster bus dx2/80 or dx4/100.

It depends.  The dx4 (all but the early production ones) can run as either 
clock doubled or clock tripled.  Most people run the dx4 at 3x the board speed.
If you are using VLB, you run the bus at this speed as well.  Therefore, the
dx2 bus is running at 40 and the dx4 at 33.  However, as I mentioned earlier, 
the dx4 can be run in clock doubled mode, hence your VL-bus is running at 
50 mhz.  This is beyond the spec, but in many cases works fine.
This is only for VLB.  For ISA busses, they all run the same speed (more or
less, I have heard of overclocking the ISA bus as well).  This is not true for
PCI bus machines.

2.  What speed does PCI run at.

PCI busses do not run the same speed as the CPU.  Thus, a dx33 and a dx2/66
will have the same bus speed : 33mhz.  This also happens to be the maximum
bus speed of the PCI bus.  Unlike VLB, attempting to exceed this does not work.
Besides, it is not easy to change this speed.  The bus speed is tied to the
external board speed of the CPU.  Hence, both the P-60 and P-66 run the bus
at 1/2 clock speed (external), and the speed of the PCI buses will be
30mhz and 33 mhz respectively.

Hope this answers more questions than it creates.
