'cause VL is a free for all on the bus, PCI has additional chips to do
bus arbitration. If you are only ever going to have 1 VL-BUS card - no PCI 
(same bus), then I expect you'll see no difference.

As soon as you get more than 1 card, 2 VL-BUS, or 1 PCI and 1 VL-BUS then
both compete for the same bus.

I have heard rumours that using VL-BUS and PCI at the same time has some 
problems in some situation, and using more than 1 VL-BUS card also has 
problems in some situations. Apparently you can run into problems with a
motherboard with both PCI and VL on it, whether or not you have any VL cards.

Or so I understand.

What I'd like to know, is why do some systems have problems using 2 PCI
cards? e.g. Adaptec and ATI PCI cards. (I think that was the combo I heard
had problems).

I'd also like to know, if PCI max'es out at 33MHz, and DX4/100 in 2/50 mode,
is PCI running at 25MHz?

I assume it's a tradeoff 2/50, faster CPU, slower PCI, 3/33, slower CPU,
faster PCI? [And heck, just how much difference can there be between the 2!]

